# d9e288acf04942568969f167a7253e4d
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:587
msgid "Why doesn't |app| let me store books in my own directory structure?"
msgstr ""

# 76b30eb981234806be00c57dc22fdef5
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:589
msgid ""
"The whole point of |app|'s library management features is that they provide "
"a search and sort based interface for locating books that is *much* more "
"efficient than any possible directory scheme you could come up with for your"
" collection. Indeed, once you become comfortable using |app|'s interface to "
"find, sort and browse your collection, you wont ever feel the need to hunt "
"through the files on your disk to find a book again. By managing books in "
"its own directory structure of Author -> Title -> Book files, |app| is able "
"to achieve a high level of reliability and standardization. To illustrate "
"why a search/tagging based interface is superior to folders, consider the "
"following. Suppose your book collection is nicely sorted into folders with "
"the following scheme::"
msgstr ""

# 56f5df568a654b03afbe5baa268e3562
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:593
msgid ""
"Now this makes it very easy to find for example all science fiction books by"
" Isaac Asimov in the Foundation series. But suppose you want to find all "
"unread science fiction books. There's no easy way to do this with this "
"folder scheme, you would instead need a folder scheme that looks like::"
msgstr ""

# e63a6362b9954545bee38c16500315de
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:597
msgid ""
"In |app|, you would instead use tags to mark genre and read status and then "
"just use a simple search query like ``tag:scifi and not tag:read``. |app| "
"even has a nice graphical interface, so you don't need to learn its search "
"language instead you can just click on tags to include or exclude them from "
"the search."
msgstr ""

# 445b46d740ec4c09b73bd569061617d5
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:599
msgid ""
"To those of you that claim that you need access to the filesystem to so that"
" you can have access to your books over the network, |app| has an excellent "
"content server that gives you access to your calibre library over the net."
msgstr ""

# ef8eb97dedac43d2a8b0f88e8e8a69f0
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:601
msgid ""
"If you are worried that someday |app| will cease to be developed, leaving "
"all your books marooned in its folder structure, explore the powerful \"Save"
" to Disk\" feature in |app| that lets you export all your files into a "
"folder structure of arbitrary complexity based on their metadata."
msgstr ""

# 1512b39b747748cb8a2814efeb7efee6
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:603
msgid ""
"Finally, the reason there are numbers at the end of every title folder, is "
"for *robustness*. That number is the id number of the book record in the "
"|app| database. The presence of the number allows you to have multiple "
"records with the same title and author names. It is also part of what allows"
" |app| to magically regenerate the database with all metadata if the "
"database file gets corrupted. Given that |app|'s mission is to get you to "
"stop storing metadata in filenames and stop using the filesystem to find "
"things, the increased robustness afforded by the id numbers is well worth "
"the uglier folder names."
msgstr ""

# 3f3b19b59243479abbb173befed2e954
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:605
msgid ""
"If you are still not convinced, then I'm afraid |app| is not for you. Look "
"elsewhere for your book cataloguing needs. Just so we're clear, **this is "
"not going to change**. Kindly do not contact us in an attempt to get us to "
"change this."
msgstr ""

# 7bd4b0e5f1cf450d9659b87197fe263c
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:608
msgid "Why doesn't |app| have a column for foo?"
msgstr ""

# b652f0005ef5458a98e591f359489c68
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:609
msgid ""
"|app| is designed to have columns for the most frequently and widely used "
"fields. In addition, you can add any columns you like. Columns can be added "
"via :guilabel:`Preferences->Interface->Add your own columns`. Watch the "
"tutorial `UI Power tips <http://calibre-ebook.com/demo#tutorials>`_ to learn"
" how to create your own columns."
msgstr ""

# ef40f06e83bf467195dc24822d1ee1d2
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:612
msgid ""
"You can also create \"virtual columns\" that contain combinations of the "
"metadata from other columns. In the add column dialog  use the "
":guilabel:`Quick create` links to easily create columns to show the book "
"ISBN, formats or the time the book was last modified. For more details, see "
":ref:`templatelangcalibre`."
msgstr ""

# 9294e70a562e4db598ddc8b7319fc76d
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:616
msgid "Can I have a column showing the formats or the ISBN?"
msgstr ""

# b968f7f1482e4eba9bb6b345fe54a55f
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:617
msgid ""
"Yes, you can. Follow the instructions in the answer above for adding custom "
"columns."
msgstr ""

# 266beff1215e42bda22767dade97553c
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:620
msgid "How do I move my |app| library from one computer to another?"
msgstr ""

# 8cbb1bf7774a43708eb416339e425b25
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:621
msgid ""
"Simply copy the |app| library folder from the old to the new computer. You "
"can find out what the library folder is by clicking the calibre icon in the "
"toolbar. The very first item is the path to the library folder. Now on the "
"new computer, start |app| for the first time. It will run the Welcome Wizard"
" asking you for the location of the |app| library. Point it to the "
"previously copied folder. If the computer you are transferring to already "
"has a calibre installation, then the Welcome wizard wont run. In that case, "
"right-click the |app| icon in the tooolbar and point it to the newly copied "
"directory. You will now have two |app| libraries on your computer and you "
"can switch between them by clicking the |app| icon on the toolbar. "
"Transferring your library in this manner preserver all your metadata, tags, "
"custom columns, etc."
msgstr ""

# 9fad040a70784a978d65c7e74cc54d39
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:633
msgid ""
"Note that if you are transferring between different types of computers (for "
"example Windows to OS X) then after doing the above you should also right-"
"click the |app| icon on the tool bar, select Library Maintenance and run the"
" Check Library action. It will warn you about any problems in your library, "
"which you should fix by hand."
msgstr ""

# 2d966de91e7e40c79d2b8ebcf62f7807
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:639
msgid ""
"A |app| library is just a folder which contains all the book files and their"
" metadata. All the metadata is stored in a single file called metadata.db, "
"in the top level folder. If this file gets corrupted, you may see an empty "
"list of books in |app|. In this case you can ask |app| to restore your books"
" by doing a right-click on the |app| icon in the toolbar and selecting "
"Library Maintenance->Restore Library."
msgstr ""

# ab5d3227809244fdb6085e626e2341a2
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:642
msgid "The list of books in |app| is blank!"
msgstr ""

# 029a00e128574ff8a67a20fe1fbf952d
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:644
msgid ""
"In order to understand why that happened, you have to understand what a "
"|app| library is. At the most basic level, a |app| library is just a folder."
" Whenever you add a book to |app|, that book's files are copied into this "
"folder (arranged into sub folders by author and title). Inside the |app| "
"library folder, at the top level, you will see a file called metadata.db. "
"This file is where |app| stores the metadata like title/author/rating/tags "
"etc. for *every* book in your |app| library. The list of books that |app| "
"displays is created by reading the contents of this metadata.db file."
msgstr ""

# c9029430dba040118921c12a4eb9ea55
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:653
msgid "There can be two reasons why |app| is showing a empty list of books:"
msgstr ""

# 287967e310484ac2b05eeaad594158f6
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:655
msgid ""
"Your |app| library folder changed its location. This can happen if it was on"
" an external disk and the drive letter for that disk changed. Or if you "
"accidentally moved the folder. In this case, |app| cannot find its library "
"and so starts up with an empty library instead. To remedy this, do a right-"
"click on the |app| icon in the |app| toolbar and select Switch/create "
"library. Click the little blue icon to select the new location of your |app|"
" library and click OK."
msgstr ""

# eb4db75e46f84603b8ababcfef6189df
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:663
msgid ""
"Your metadata.db file was deleted/corrupted. In this case, you can ask |app|"
" to rebuild the metadata.db from its backups. Right click the |app| icon in "
"the |app| toolbar and select Library maintenance->Restore database. |app| "
"will automatically rebuild metadata.db."
msgstr ""

# 0e72cafb95734b1baf0b183f3c4b29e1
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:669
msgid "I am getting errors with my calibre library on a networked drive/NAS?"
msgstr ""

# f70d1ab13bac44b8a9c1ff6eb44bb8af
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:671
msgid "**Do not put your calibre library on a networked drive**."
msgstr ""

# 63a82596efa14a17988c94cf7e35d26d
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:673
msgid ""
"A filesystem is a complex beast. Most network filesystems lack various "
"filesystem features that |app| uses. Some dont support file locking, some "
"dont support hardlinking, some are just flaky. Additionally, |app| is a "
"single user application, if you accidentally run two copies of |app| on the "
"same networked library, bad things will happen. Finally, different OSes "
"impose different limitations on filesystems, so if you share your networked "
"drive across OSes, once again, bad things *will happen*."
msgstr ""

# fc3cf2ec217849268ac9051fbebd464b
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:681
msgid ""
"Consider using the |app| Content Server to make your books available on "
"other computers. Run |app| on a single computer and access it via the "
"Content Server or a Remote Desktop solution."
msgstr ""

# 569756dd6395438387ca39fd3468aaf4
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:685
msgid ""
"If you must share the actual library, use a file syncing tool like DropBox "
"or rsync instead of a networked drive. If you are using a file-syncing tool "
"it is **essential** that you make sure that both |app| and the file syncing "
"tool do not try to access the |app| library at the same time. In other "
"words, **do not** run the file syncing tool and |app| at the same time."
msgstr ""

# 32460f90c7ef4771b46013a3827851d9
#: ../../home/kovid/work/calibre/manual/faq.rst:692
msgid ""
"Even with these tools there is danger of data corruption/loss, so only do "
"this if you are willing to live with that risk. In particular, be aware that"
" **Google Drive** is incompatible with |app|, if you put your |app| library "
"in Google Drive, **you will suffer data loss**. See `this thread "
"<http://www.mobileread.com/forums/showthread.php?t=205581>`_ for details."
msgstr ""

